moves.name: Okami Shuffle
notes: There are gaps inbetween each phase that can potentially lead to a punish
First phase (fire) has 10 high durability points
Second phase (ice) 3 high durability points for each projectile
Third phase (lightning) 5 high priority durability points each
Final hit (lightning bolt) 5 high priority durability points
It's generally impossible to get all 55 hits of Okami Shuffle to hit and more realistically will get about 20 - 30 hits on average depending on character size and distance from opponent
Damage value shown are for 30 hits

moves.name: Standing Light
notes: Effective as a pushblock bait by linking Standing Light into itself
moves.description: A quick jab with not much utility outside of converting tight air confirms into a grounded string and setting up frame traps. A rarely used button since buster charging is recommended with L.

moves.name: Standing Medium
notes: Standing Medium has a small hitbox behind Zero which allow
moves.description: A decent poke that moves Zero slightly forward. Standing Medium isn't used much outside of some combo routes.

moves.name: Standing Heavy
moves.description: One of Zero's best normals and one of the best normals in the game. Standing Heavy has a very large hitbox in front of and above him that can be used as an anti-air and a pressure tool.

moves.name: Special
moves.description: A standard launcher with a good hitbox above Zero's head. Not worth using as an anti-air when Standing Heavy and Crouching Heavy exist.

moves.name: Crouching Light
moves.description: Crouching Light is Zero's fastest normal and one of the fastest lows in the game. A great button for setting up staggers for frame traps as well as for high/low mixups. Players must be comfortable with buster switching to get the most utility out of this button.

moves.name: Crouching Medium
moves.description: Crouching Medium is a fantastic low poke with good range that shrinks Zero's hurtbox down. It moves Zero forward while also able to hit behind creating strong mixups in certain situations.

moves.name: Crouching Heavy
moves.description: Another one of Zero's great anti-airs. Also useful early in combos to add good damage without heavily scaling combo like Standing Heavy and Shippuga (6H).

moves.name: Air Light
moves.description: Air Light is a quick kick that appears slightly below him. It's more useful as a falling button rather than rising, except when using it as an instant overhead.

moves.name: Air Medium
moves.description: A great air poke with a hitbox above him that makes it useful for calling out opponent's air actions. It's especially powerful when Level 3 Buster is charged since it leads to full confirms.

moves.name: Air Heavy
moves.description: A good button with a great hitbox that is nearly impossible to punish. It's hardly used since it's not special cancellable and because Kuenzan, "pizza cutter", is all around a better option.

moves.name: Air Special
moves.description: A slower air poke than Air Medium but has a a much larger hitbox above it making it still very strong in some situations. Very useful for super jump confirms since it has a ton of hitstun and pushes the opponent down.

moves.name: Shippuga
moves.description: Shippuga is a great pressure tool with a large hitbox in front of Zero while also moving him forward. One of Zero's most important pressure tools since it can negate bad pushblock timings as well as lead to infinite blockstrings and unblockables when in Sougenmu.

moves.name: Kuenzan
moves.description: Kuenzan, a.k.a "pizza cutter", is one of the best buttons in the whole game. It's massive hitbox makes it nearly impossible to throw or anti-air. It can be used pretty freely without worry. The only downside is that it is not special or buster cancellable.

moves.name: Hadangeki L
moves.description: The slowest moving version of Hadangeki with the longest startup. The tradeoff of its longer startup is its superior frame data and it has the shortest recovery which makes great for stacking fireballs together or walking in behind it.

moves.name: Hadangeki M
moves.description: The fastest moving version of Hadangeki with the fastest startup. This is probably to most commonly used version due to its fast speed.

moves.name: Hadangeki H
moves.description: Hadangeki H is the middle point in terms of speed and startup. It fires two projectiles and has the most damage and durability of the 3 versions. Zero is capable of putting out a ton of projectile durability when Hadangeki H is cancelled into Level 3 Buster.

moves.name: Ryuenjin L
moves.description: A short range DP without any invincibility frames. One of Zero's more useless moves. Ryuenjin L doesn't hit or travel very high so trying to use it as an anti-air is pointless.

moves.name: Ryuenjin M
moves.description: Similar to Ryuenjin L, not very useful in neutral as an anti-air. It does have some uses in some combos since there is a bit of guaranteed hitstun at the end of the special where the opponent falls down slightly, giving you some extra time to charge buster, normalize the height, and continue the combo with a buster cancel.

moves.name: Ryuenjin H
moves.description: The most viable version of Ryuenjin. It has a pretty large and active hitbox that makes it decent as anti-air even though it has no invincibility. When combined with an assist like Jam Session, it becomes even more viable as it allows Zero to confirm the hit at any height.

moves.name: Raikousen L
moves.description: Raikousen L sends Zero down at a 45 degree angle. It's most commonly used for combo extensions with buster cancels and for incoming mixups since it can pass through opponents. It's the key to Zero's "lightning loop".

moves.name: Raikousen M
moves.description: Raikousen M sends Zero across the screen in a straight line. It's more commonly used as a movement tool or a long range poke with a buster cancel available. The guaranteed soft knockdown is a great way to call out air movement at any height.

moves.name: Raikousen H
moves.description: Raikousen H shoots Zero up at a 45 degree angle. It is another one of Zero's great anti-air tools when combined with an instant buster cancel. Also incredibly useful at getting Zero to super jump height without having to use his command dash.

moves.name: Hienkyaku L
moves.description: A short fast moving dash that can pass through opponents. Effective at either creating fast left/right mixups with Level 3 Buster or negating pushblocks.

moves.name: Hienkyaku M
moves.description: Hienkyaku M moves in the same trajectory as Hienkyaku L but travels much further. Even better at creating left/right mixups because it can still put Zero behind the opponent even his previous button was pushblocked.

moves.name: Hienkyaku H
moves.description: Hienkyaku H sends very up and then back down in a very tight parabolic angle. It's capabable of stealing the corner from the opponent allowing for ambiguious mixups. Zero is able to perform any actions as soon as he reaches the peak of the command dash.

moves.name: Air Hienkyaku L
moves.description: Instead of moving forward like its grounded version, Air Hienkyaku L sends Zero straight to the ground. One of his key components to his great air movement allowing to go from super jump height to the ground in an instant.

moves.name: Air Hienkyaku M
moves.description: Follows the same trajectory of his grounded Hienkyaku M. Useful for clearing horizontal space quickly without having to use Zero's air dash.

moves.name: Air Hienkyaku H
moves.description: Follows the same trajectory of his grounded Hienkyaku H. Allows Zero to get incredibly high in the air without having to super jump to retain the ability to call assists.

moves.name: Sentsuizan L
moves.description: Acts as a sort of fake out move that freezes Zero in place for a couple of frames. Useful for stalling out in the air or faking out a Raikousen.

moves.name: Sentsuizan M
notes: Launcher properties when used in air combo after Standing S
moves.description: A divekick that sends Zero down at a very steep angle. A good alternative to Air Hienkyaku L to quickly advance to the floor while also putting a hitbox below him.

moves.name: Sentsuizan H
notes: Launcher properties when used in air combo after Standing S
moves.description: A divekick that sends Zero down at a 45 degree angle used as his primary OTG. The wider angle of this version over Sentsuizan M can be used to create mixups from super jump height when combined with mixup.

moves.name: Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 1)
moves.description: Upon release, Zero shoots out a tiny slow moving blue buster. Not incredibly useful outside of some scenarios where you are trying to frame trap an opponent.

moves.name: Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 2)
moves.description: A slightly more durable, faster, and more damaging projectile than the level 1 buster. The main difference is that it cannot be destroyed with normals unlike the level 1 buster.

moves.name: Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 3)
notes: Beam - 3 frames x 3 low durability point
moves.description: Level 3 Buster is one of the biggest neutral defining tools in the game. Its a projectile with beam durability pierces through opponents and beats out almost every non-super projectile in the game. It opens up his neutral immensely since nearly all of his normals and all of his specials are Level 3 Buster cancellable.

moves.name: Air Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 1)
moves.description: Air Level 1 Buster carries all the same properties of its grounded version except Zero shoots it down at a 45 degree angle. Not much utility outside using it to stall in the air in some matchups.

moves.name: Air Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 2)
moves.description: Shoots a green buster down at 45 degree angle. Similar to Level 1, you wont use this much outside of trying to stall in the air or pepper the screen with extra projectiles.

moves.name: Air Hyper Zero Blaster (Level 3)
notes: Beam - 3 frames x 3 low durability point
moves.description: Just like its grounded variant, Air Level 3 Buster enables Zero to set the pace of neutral with buster cancelled specials. Since it's a guaranteed soft knockdown, you can use it to confirm any hit from any height.

moves.name: Rekkoha
notes: Beam - 30 frames x 1 high durability point
moves.description: Rekkoha is a rarely used combo finisher, especially since lightning loops exist. Due to its rather slow startup, it will only work in specific combo routes.

moves.name: Sougenmu
notes: Creates a shadow that mimics Zero 16 frames later
Shadow lasts for 300 frames and disappears if Zero uses any other super
Zero does not gain any meter while Sougenmu is active
moves.description: Arguably the best install super in the game. Sougenmu creates a clone of himself that mimics every action 16 frames later. This lets Zero put out double the durability with his projectiles, create unblockables, and generally bully his opponents with buttons.

moves.name: Genmu Zero
moves.description: Zero's level 3 super that sends out a massive projectile across the screen. Genmu Zero is a useful ender in happy birthday combos to avoid combo drops during lightning loops when an assist dies.

assists.name: Ryuenjin H
assists.description: A multi-hitting DP assist without any invincibility that appears slightly in front of the player.

assists.name: Hadangeki M
assists.description: A single hit, fast moving projectile.

assists.name: Shippuga
assists.description: A slower assist that sends Zero forward with his saber out.
